# Atlas Database Schema — Complete Guide

Every table, every column, explained in plain English.

---

## PostgreSQL (Relational Data)

### 1. `companies` — The master list of companies you're tracking

| Column | Type | What it stores |
|---|---|---|
| `id` | Auto-incrementing integer | Internal ID, auto-generated |
| `ticker` | `VARCHAR(10)`, unique | Stock symbol, e.g. `AAPL`, `RELIANCE` |
| `name` | `VARCHAR(255)` | Full company name, e.g. `Apple Inc.` |
| `cik` | `VARCHAR(20)` | SEC's "Central Index Key" — a unique ID the SEC assigns to every company that files with them. Needed to look up filings on EDGAR |

**Why this table exists:** It's the central reference. Every filing, news mention, and market tick links back to a company via ticker or `company_id`.

---

### 2. `filings` — SEC regulatory filings (10-K, 10-Q, 8-K, etc.)

| Column | Type | What it stores |
|---|---|---|
| `id` | Auto-incrementing integer | Internal ID |
| `company_id` | `INT` → references `companies(id)` | Which company filed this |
| `form_type` | `VARCHAR(20)` | The type of SEC form: `10-K` (annual report), `10-Q` (quarterly), `8-K` (major event), `S-1` (IPO filing), etc. |
| `filed_at` | `DATE` | When it was filed with the SEC |
| [url](file:///e:/terminal_proj/ingestion/news/rss_aggregator.py#125-128) | `TEXT` | Direct link to the filing on SEC EDGAR |

**Why:** When you download filings from EDGAR, they're logged here so you know what you have and can link them to chunks.

---

### 3. `filing_chunks` — Searchable pieces of filing documents

| Column | Type | What it stores |
|---|---|---|
| `id` | Auto-incrementing integer | Internal ID |
| `filing_id` | `INT` → references `filings(id)` | Which filing this chunk belongs to |
| `content` | `TEXT` | The actual text content — a paragraph or section from the filing |
| `embedding` | `vector(384)` | A 384-dimensional vector (array of 384 numbers) that mathematically represents the meaning of the text. Generated by the `all-MiniLM-L6-v2` model. Used for semantic search — "find paragraphs that *mean* something similar to my question" |

**Why:** SEC filings are enormous (100+ pages). You can't search them efficiently as-is. So each filing is split into chunks, each chunk gets an embedding vector, and you can do AI-powered semantic search across all filings.

---

### 4. `port_geofences` — Geographic boundaries of ports

| Column | Type | What it stores |
|---|---|---|
| `id` | Auto-incrementing integer | Internal ID |
| `port_name` | `VARCHAR(255)` | Name of the port, e.g. `Port of Singapore` |
| `geom` | `GEOMETRY(POLYGON, 4326)` | A polygon (shape) on the map defining the port's boundary. `4326` is the GPS coordinate system (latitude/longitude). Stored using PostGIS |

**Why:** To detect when a ship enters or leaves a port. You define the port as a polygon on a map, then check if a ship's GPS point falls inside it.

---

### 5. `ship_positions` — GPS tracking data for ships

| Column | Type | What it stores |
|---|---|---|
| `id` | Auto-incrementing integer | Internal ID |
| `mmsi` | `VARCHAR(20)` | Maritime Mobile Service Identity — a unique 9-digit number assigned to every ship's radio equipment. Like a phone number for ships |
| `timestamp` | `TIMESTAMPTZ` | When this position was recorded (with timezone) |
| `geom` | `GEOMETRY(POINT, 4326)` | The ship's GPS location (latitude + longitude) as a point on the map |
| `speed` | `FLOAT` | Ship's speed in knots |
| `heading` | `FLOAT` | Direction the ship is pointing, in degrees (0° = North, 90° = East, etc.) |

**Why:** Tracking ship movements reveals supply chain patterns — which ports are congested, where oil tankers are heading, trade route disruptions, etc.

---

### 6. `news_articles` — All news from every source

| Column | Type | What it stores |
|---|---|---|
| `id` | Auto-incrementing integer | Internal ID |
| `source_name` | `VARCHAR(100)` | Which ingestion source: `rss`, `finnhub`, `newsdata`, `gdelt` |
| `source_id` | `VARCHAR(255)` | The article's ID from the original source (so you can trace it back) |
| `title` | `TEXT` | Headline of the article |
| `summary` | `TEXT` | Short description or first paragraph |
| `content` | `TEXT` | Full article text (if available — some APIs only give summaries) |
| [url](file:///e:/terminal_proj/ingestion/news/rss_aggregator.py#125-128) | `TEXT`, unique | Link to the original article. Unique constraint prevents duplicate articles |
| `author` | `VARCHAR(255)` | Who wrote it |
| `category` | `VARCHAR(100)` | Topic category: `business`, `politics`, `technology`, `world`, etc. |
| `language` | `VARCHAR(10)` | Language code: [en](file:///e:/terminal_proj/ingestion/news/finnhub_news_downloader.py#59-73), `hi`, [de](file:///e:/terminal_proj/ingestion/news/gdelt_downloader.py#80-303), etc. |
| `country` | `VARCHAR(10)` | Country code where the news is about/from: `US`, `IN`, `GB`, etc. |
| `image_url` | `TEXT` | URL to the article's thumbnail image |
| `published_at` | `TIMESTAMPTZ` | When the article was published |
| `ingested_at` | `TIMESTAMPTZ`, defaults to `NOW()` | When *you* pulled it into your database |
| `embedding` | `vector(384)` | Semantic vector for AI search (same as filing_chunks — for future use) |

**Why:** This is the **unified news table**. No matter which source (RSS, Finnhub, NewsData, GDELT), all articles end up here in the same format, deduplicated by URL.

---

### 7. `gdelt_events` — Geopolitical events from GDELT

| Column | Type | What it stores |
|---|---|---|
| `id` | Auto-incrementing integer | Internal ID |
| `global_event_id` | `BIGINT`, unique | GDELT's own event ID |
| `event_date` | `DATE` | When the event happened |
| `actor1_name` | `VARCHAR(255)` | Who did it — e.g. `UNITED STATES`, `CHINA`, person/org name |
| `actor1_country` | `VARCHAR(10)` | Actor 1's country code |
| `actor1_type` | `VARCHAR(100)` | What kind of actor: `GOV` (government), `MIL` (military), `BUS` (business), etc. |
| `actor2_name` | `VARCHAR(255)` | Who it was done to |
| `actor2_country` | `VARCHAR(10)` | Actor 2's country code |
| `actor2_type` | `VARCHAR(100)` | Actor 2's type |
| `event_code` | `VARCHAR(10)` | CAMEO code — a standardized code for the type of event (e.g., `14` = Protest, `18` = Assault) |
| [event_description](file:///e:/terminal_proj/ingestion/news/gdelt_downloader.py#142-146) | `VARCHAR(255)` | Human-readable version of the event code |
| `goldstein_scale` | `FLOAT` | A score from -10 to +10 measuring the event's potential impact on stability. Negative = destabilizing (war, conflict). Positive = cooperative (peace deal, aid) |
| `num_mentions` | `INT` | How many times this event was mentioned across all sources |
| `num_sources` | `INT` | How many distinct news sources reported it |
| `num_articles` | `INT` | Total articles about this event |
| `avg_tone` | `FLOAT` | Average emotional tone of the coverage (-100 to +100). Negative = hostile/negative language. Positive = positive language |
| `geom` | `GEOMETRY(POINT, 4326)` | Where the event happened (GPS coordinates) |
| `source_url` | `TEXT` | Link to one of the source articles |

**Why:** GDELT captures *structured* geopolitical events — not just news text, but who did what to whom, where, and how the world reacted. Useful for risk analysis, trade disruption prediction, commodity price impact.

---

### 8. `news_ticker_mentions` — Links articles to stock tickers

| Column | Type | What it stores |
|---|---|---|
| `id` | Auto-incrementing integer | Internal ID |
| `article_id` | `INT` → references `news_articles(id)` | Which article mentions this company |
| `ticker` | `VARCHAR(10)` | Stock symbol mentioned, e.g. `TSLA` |
| `sentiment_score` | `FLOAT` | How positive/negative the article is about this company (-1.0 to +1.0) |
| `relevance_score` | `FLOAT` | How central the company is to the article (0 to 1.0) |

**Why:** One article can mention multiple companies. This many-to-many table lets you ask: "Show me all negative news about TSLA this week" or "Which stocks are getting the most media coverage?"

---

## ClickHouse (Time-Series / Analytics)

### 9. `market_ticks` — Raw price data (every trade)

| Column | Type | What it stores |
|---|---|---|
| `symbol` | `String` | Stock ticker, e.g. `AAPL` |
| `price` | `Float64` | Price at this instant |
| `volume` | `Float64` | Number of shares traded in this tick |
| `timestamp` | `DateTime64(3, 'UTC')` | Exact time (millisecond precision, UTC) |

**Why:** This is the raw, tick-by-tick market data from Fyers/Yahoo Finance. Every single trade event goes here.

---

### 10. `ohlcv_1min` — 1-minute candlestick bars (auto-generated)

| Column | Type | What it stores |
|---|---|---|
| `symbol` | `String` | Stock ticker |
| `minute_bucket` | `DateTime` | Which minute this candle represents |
| `open` | `Float64` | **First** price in that minute |
| `high` | `Float64` | **Highest** price |
| `low` | `Float64` | **Lowest** price |
| [close](file:///e:/terminal_proj/ingestion/news/newsdata_downloader.py#262-264) | `Float64` | **Last** price |
| `volume` | `Float64` | Total shares traded in that minute |

**Auto-populated** by a ClickHouse Materialized View (`ohlcv_1min_mv`) — whenever data goes into `market_ticks`, ClickHouse automatically aggregates it into 1-minute candles here. You never insert into this table manually.

---

### 11. `ohlcv_5min` — 5-minute candlestick bars (auto-generated)

Same columns as `ohlcv_1min`, but grouped into 5-minute windows. Also auto-populated by a Materialized View.

---

### 12. `news_sentiment_ts` — Sentiment time-series per ticker

| Column | Type | What it stores |
|---|---|---|
| `ticker` | `String` | Stock symbol |
| `source` | `String` | Where the sentiment came from (`finnhub`, `newsdata`, etc.) |
| [sentiment](file:///e:/terminal_proj/ingestion/news/finnhub_news_downloader.py#74-86) | `Float64` | Sentiment score (-1.0 to +1.0) |
| `tone` | `Float64` | Emotional tone from GDELT (-100 to +100) |
| `timestamp` | `DateTime64(3, 'UTC')` | When this sentiment was recorded |

**Why:** Track how media sentiment about a stock changes over time. Plot it alongside price to see if negative news correlates with price drops.

---

### 13. `gdelt_event_volume` — Geopolitical event trends

| Column | Type | What it stores |
|---|---|---|
| `event_code` | `String` | CAMEO event type code |
| `country` | `String` | Country code |
| `event_count` | `UInt32` | How many events of this type in this hour |
| `avg_tone` | `Float64` | Average tone of the coverage |
| `avg_goldstein` | `Float64` | Average stability impact score |
| `bucket_hour` | `DateTime` | Which hour this aggregate covers |

**Why:** Instead of querying millions of individual events, this pre-aggregated table lets you quickly answer: "How many protests happened in India this week?" or "Is conflict in the Middle East trending up?"

---

## Neo4j (Graph Relationships)

Neo4j doesn't have "columns" — it has **nodes** (things) and **relationships** (connections). Currently these node types are defined with uniqueness constraints:

| Node Label | Unique Property | What it represents |
|---|---|---|
| `:Company` | `ticker` | A company (e.g., Apple) |
| `:Filing` | `id` | An SEC filing |
| `:Ship` | `mmsi` | A vessel |
| `:Port` | `name` | A port |
| `:Article` | [url](file:///e:/terminal_proj/ingestion/news/rss_aggregator.py#125-128) | A news article |
| `:Event` | `global_event_id` | A GDELT geopolitical event |
| `:Source` | `name` | A news source (e.g., Reuters) |
| `:NewsCategory` | `name` | A topic category |

**Future relationships:** `:Company -[:FILED]-> :Filing`, `:Article -[:MENTIONS]-> :Company`, `:Ship -[:DOCKED_AT]-> :Port`, etc.

---

## Redis (Cache)

No tables — Redis stores **key-value pairs** in memory. Currently empty. Will be used for caching API responses, rate limiting, and session data.
